Jesus, man... Let me tell you a little something I learned recently - the hard way. Bettering yourself is a great goal, and one that you should absolutely keep after, but you can't let it be the only thing you're working on. This goes double if you're talking about the physical fitness side of the equation.

Since you're spending more effort on internalized improvement, you can very easily start living a more isolated existence, which can cause your social skills to atrophy. Plus, if all the interactions you remember are from before you started work on you, you're handicapping yourself and your confidence regardless of how physically fit you get.

If you're not sure how to start, find a close friend who's known to be more of an empath, and have them coach you through some online interactions with gals. Tinder is PERFECT for this, as it's low pressure and you'll feel like there's nothing wagered when talking to randos. Once you feel comfortable working light banter / flirting into text messages, start trying it in real life. Doesn't need to be someone you're super attracted to, nor does it have to be anyone you plan to spark a relationship with. Go to stores a town over, so you can practice on girls you won't have to see every day. Make every work trip an opportunity. Just do what you can to minimize the stakes of your interactions.

Once you get used to the idea of an "L" being painless, you'll start to lose your fear of it. If you're not afraid of rejection, you're unironically less likely to experience it.

Remember, gals have to deal with self doubt and imperfection, too! If you find someone before you reach the you you want to be, maybe she can help encourage you on your journey. ...maybe you can encourage her along hers!

Anonymous Fri 09 Nov 2018 04:19:12 No.19310078 Report
Quoted By:
>>19309294
Isolating oneself to achieve goals is a myth for most people. Typically the people that succeed at it already have confidence and skill in spade. A social environment is pretty critical to bettering oneself. For starters, you learn from others. Your social environment overlapping with the area you want to improve in will also give good incentive to keep at it, even when your confidence wanes. And you will be in a comfortable social environment where you can actually talk about shit you're interested in, and get respect for it.

I isolated myself out of shame. Even looking back on it, I can't say it was that strange of a decision. When you're a failure, and the people you know aren't, you start noticing that you never have anything new to say, and are repeating old stories. And you notice how old those stories get. Al Bundy "four touchdowns in one game" kind of shit. And on the other hand, if you hang with other failures, you start noticing how you're validating your positions to one another, or how they're a negative person who likes keeping themselves there by externalizing their failure (which is attractive, trust me).

But the problem is, it's an internal feeling. It doesn't go away. And it impedes you from actually achieving anything, because you're essentially punishing yourself for not having reached an arbitrary bar you've set for yourself. And it's probably very a very vague one, or far off. There's no planning to it, it's just a mythical "when I'm good enough" kind of thing. Some undefined point in the future, with no actual steps towards reaching it.

How do I know all this? I'm an expert on failure. It's all experience, baby.
